{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619561"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:33:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:33:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16565"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16565"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9256"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75759"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9256"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16565"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61272"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7180"},{"type":"tags","id":"8505"},{"type":"tags","id":"10346"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21930"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75759"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHydrocephalus occurs when there\u0027s an abnormal accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) in the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures allows unidirectional flow of cerebrospinal fluid?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pacchionian bodies","Arachnoid granulations","Choroid plexus","Ependymal cells","Dural venous sinuses"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArachnoid granulations\u003C/strong\u003E are specialised structures that project from the arachnoid membrane into the dural venous sinuses. They contain one-way valves that allow CSF to flow from the subarachnoid space into the venous system but prevent blood from flowing back into the CSF space.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPacchionian bodies\u003C/strong\u003E is an outdated term for arachnoid granulations and is no longer preferred in modern medical terminology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Echoroid plexus\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for producing CSF through active secretion but does not regulate its directional flow. It is located within the ventricles and produces approximately 500 mL of CSF daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpendymal cells\u003C/strong\u003E line the ventricles and central canal of the spinal cord. While they are important in CSF circulation, they do not regulate its directional flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edural venous sinuses\u003C/strong\u003E are the vessels that receive CSF from the arachnoid granulations, but they themselves do not regulate the direction of CSF flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding CSF circulation is crucial in diagnosing and treating conditions such as hydrocephalus, where CSF flow or absorption is impaired. The unidirectional flow through arachnoid granulations is essential for maintaining normal intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Arachnoid granulations are specialised structures that allow unidirectional flow of cerebrospinal fluid from the subarachnoid space into the dural venous sinuses.","Cerebrospinal fluid is produced by the choroid plexus and circulates through the ventricular system before being absorbed by arachnoid granulations."],"references":["Shah T, Leurgans SE, Mehta RI, Yang J, Galloway CA, de Mesy Bentley KL, Schneider JA, Mehta RI. Arachnoid granulations are lymphatic conduits that communicate with bone marrow and dura-arachnoid stroma. J Exp Med. 2023 Feb 6;220(2):e20220618. doi: 10.1084/jem.20220618. Epub 2022 Dec 5. PMID: 36469302; PMCID: PMC9728136",".Kan P, Stevens EA, Couldwell WT. Incidental giant arachnoid granulation. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2006 Aug;27(7):1491-2. PMID: 16908565; PMCID: PMC7977517.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61272"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16565"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61272"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T14:29:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T14:30:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9256"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75759"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"headin